maternal ancestors hy any title whatever: Theodosius 11 added lucra nuptialia (dos and donatio propter nuptias), and reformed the eules as to the intestata succession to peculium adventitium and preferring the child's own issue to the pater, who by Leo and Anthemius was postponed also to brothers and sisters. Justinian, as he says in § 1, included under peculium adventitium (which in the text is called ‘res quae adquisitionem effugiunt') all that the child acquired otherwise than ex re patris or-in the way of peculium castrense or quasicastrense: under his legislation con· sequently achild might have rights over property of three kinds, over one ol which he had the absolute control ; one over which his pater had a usufruct, while he was its dominus; and lastly peculium profectitium, property ol the pater which the latter could resume at will, and oi which he himself had only the use and enjoyment. lf he were emancipated, the father originally was entitled absolutely to half the peculium ad- ventitium, ‘quasi pro pretio emancipationis :² the change which Justinian made in this matter is mentioned in § 2.
